1
00:00:00,090 --> 00:00:02,700
- Lots of teenagers are
about to get very rich.

2
00:00:02,700 --> 00:00:03,533
- Why is that?

3
00:00:03,533 --> 00:00:06,300
- Well, the data strongly
shows that traditional jobs

4
00:00:06,300 --> 00:00:09,090
are being replaced and
online jobs are booming.

5
00:00:09,090 --> 00:00:11,460
- But surely that means
there'll be too much competition

6
00:00:11,460 --> 00:00:12,660
in the online space.

7
00:00:12,660 --> 00:00:14,640
- Well, teenagers have an advantage,

8
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:17,670
as they understand the online
world better than anyone else.

9
00:00:17,670 --> 00:00:18,930
It's just second nature.

10
00:00:18,930 --> 00:00:21,000
- But Mark, I dunno what to do.

11
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:22,710
- Well, that's why I'm gonna be revealing

12
00:00:22,710 --> 00:00:26,250
the 7.5 best paid online
jobs for teenagers.

13
00:00:26,250 --> 00:00:28,050
And this isn't any old list.

14
00:00:28,050 --> 00:00:31,230
For each one, I'm gonna
provide a real life example

15
00:00:31,230 --> 00:00:33,960
of a teenager currently
killing it in that job.

16
00:00:33,960 --> 00:00:36,330
Job one is an advertising deal broker.

17
00:00:36,330 --> 00:00:38,370
Teenagers doing this job earn as much

18
00:00:38,370 --> 00:00:42,060
as 100 to $120,000 per year.

19
00:00:42,060 --> 00:00:44,760
In 2021, I bought a Tesla Model 3,

20
00:00:44,760 --> 00:00:46,770
and I set myself a bit of a challenge.

21
00:00:46,770 --> 00:00:48,960
I wanted to see if it
was possible to use lots

22
00:00:48,960 --> 00:00:52,170
of different side hustles to
earn back the price of the car.

23
00:00:52,170 --> 00:00:54,270
One of the ideas my son and I came up with

24
00:00:54,270 --> 00:00:56,310
was to get it wrapped like a racecar

25
00:00:56,310 --> 00:00:58,920
which would involve securing
paid advertisements.

26
00:00:58,920 --> 00:01:01,980
At this point, we received
a cold email from a teenager

27
00:01:01,980 --> 00:01:04,680
called Christian
completely out of the blue

28
00:01:04,680 --> 00:01:07,350
who said that he was able
to secure the sponsorship

29
00:01:07,350 --> 00:01:10,020
we required for a 30% commission.

30
00:01:10,020 --> 00:01:13,860
Christian managed to get an
offer of $30,000 on the table.

31
00:01:13,860 --> 00:01:17,730
Had we accepted this deal, he
would've made a sweat $9,000

32
00:01:17,730 --> 00:01:20,310
for essentially matching us with the brand

33
00:01:20,310 --> 00:01:22,020
and acting as the middle man.

34
00:01:22,020 --> 00:01:24,660
In the end, Curtis managed
to secure a different deal

35
00:01:24,660 --> 00:01:27,240
with public.com, so we went with them.

36
00:01:27,240 --> 00:01:29,130
However, Christian has managed to secure

37
00:01:29,130 --> 00:01:30,810
many of these deals in the past.

38
00:01:30,810 --> 00:01:32,700
That's why we can still
offer you a free stock

39
00:01:32,700 --> 00:01:35,310
worth all the way up to $1,000 from Public

40
00:01:35,310 --> 00:01:36,870
with the link in the description.

41
00:01:36,870 --> 00:01:39,480
Christian told me that the
best way to be successful

42
00:01:39,480 --> 00:01:42,690
with this job is to make
friends in the right places.

43
00:01:42,690 --> 00:01:44,760
He described it a lot like a jungle

44
00:01:44,760 --> 00:01:47,460
where one branch would lead
to the next one and so on.

45
00:01:47,460 --> 00:01:49,830
Once you start working
with one big company,

46
00:01:49,830 --> 00:01:52,620
it becomes a lot easier,
as you can reference them

47
00:01:52,620 --> 00:01:55,620
as a past client and therefore demonstrate

48
00:01:55,620 --> 00:01:58,320
that you have experience in
the areas that they require.

49
00:01:58,320 --> 00:01:59,730
So how does he do it?

50
00:01:59,730 --> 00:02:02,430
He uses different software
to get the email addresses

51
00:02:02,430 --> 00:02:05,070
of influencers and just fires off messages

52
00:02:05,070 --> 00:02:06,270
until he gets a bite.

53
00:02:06,270 --> 00:02:08,220
Then he evaluates the needs of the clients

54
00:02:08,220 --> 00:02:11,220
that contact him back and
runs a similar campaign

55
00:02:11,220 --> 00:02:13,170
focused on reaching out to brands

56
00:02:13,170 --> 00:02:14,550
on the influencer's behalf.

57
00:02:14,550 --> 00:02:16,117
It kind of reminds me of the book

58
00:02:16,117 --> 00:02:18,420
"How To Win Friends & Influence People,"

59
00:02:18,420 --> 00:02:20,970
where Dale Carnegie
talks about sending mail

60
00:02:20,970 --> 00:02:23,370
to powerful people and getting replies,

61
00:02:23,370 --> 00:02:24,900
only the modern-day version.

62
00:02:24,900 --> 00:02:26,760
If we learn anything from Christian

63
00:02:26,760 --> 00:02:29,970
it's the power of a good
reference and relationships.

64
00:02:29,970 --> 00:02:32,160
Always do your best work
because you never know

65
00:02:32,160 --> 00:02:34,230
where something might lead in the future.

66
00:02:34,230 --> 00:02:37,410
Job two is a Discord
community manager for Web3.

67
00:02:37,410 --> 00:02:40,530
These teens make more than $70,000 a year,

68
00:02:40,530 --> 00:02:42,990
depending on their multitasking ability.

69
00:02:42,990 --> 00:02:44,880
When it comes to marketing for Gen Z,

70
00:02:44,880 --> 00:02:46,350
community is everything.

71
00:02:46,350 --> 00:02:48,630
Every brand under the
sun is trying to build

72
00:02:48,630 --> 00:02:50,400
a community around their product.

73
00:02:50,400 --> 00:02:52,740
This is actually the
main reason why Gymshark

74
00:02:52,740 --> 00:02:54,780
have set up their first store in London.

75
00:02:54,780 --> 00:02:56,820
- The real purpose of
this store needs to be

76
00:02:56,820 --> 00:02:58,980
to really cultivate the Gymshark community

77
00:02:58,980 --> 00:03:00,210
and connect with people.

78
00:03:00,210 --> 00:03:01,860
- Now, if you've ever used Discord,

79
00:03:01,860 --> 00:03:04,230
then you've probably
met a community manager.

80
00:03:04,230 --> 00:03:07,020
They're like the glue that
holds everything together.

81
00:03:07,020 --> 00:03:10,410
I know a guy called Harry
who hires community managers.

82
00:03:10,410 --> 00:03:12,180
He said that he wouldn't bat an eyelid

83
00:03:12,180 --> 00:03:14,760
at paying more than $2,000 per week

84
00:03:14,760 --> 00:03:17,370
if they were good at the job
and represented the brand

85
00:03:17,370 --> 00:03:18,750
in a positive light.

86
00:03:18,750 --> 00:03:21,390
Additionally, if you are
good at multitasking,

87
00:03:21,390 --> 00:03:23,970
there's nothing stopping you
from being a community manager

88
00:03:23,970 --> 00:03:26,820
for three or four
projects at the same time,

89
00:03:26,820 --> 00:03:28,350
which means big money.

90
00:03:28,350 --> 00:03:31,320
The job of the community manager
is to be on the front line.

91
00:03:31,320 --> 00:03:33,510
You have to tell the story of the brand,

92
00:03:33,510 --> 00:03:35,430
be customer service and support,

93
00:03:35,430 --> 00:03:37,650
as well as supporting
people when they're down

94
00:03:37,650 --> 00:03:39,750
and paying attention to global events.

95
00:03:39,750 --> 00:03:41,820
You need to be able to
pause your schedule,

96
00:03:41,820 --> 00:03:43,920
be active when people are looking for you,

97
00:03:43,920 --> 00:03:46,170
and listen when people
need your attention.

98
00:03:46,170 --> 00:03:49,200
Above all, you have to
be the voice of the CEO,

99
00:03:49,200 --> 00:03:51,660
but not always speak on
behalf of the company.

100
00:03:51,660 --> 00:03:54,750
Job three is writing scripts
for content creators.

101
00:03:54,750 --> 00:03:57,690
These teams can earn upwards of $100,000,

102
00:03:57,690 --> 00:04:00,600
but can go a lot higher
depending on the type of content

103
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:01,920
and your experience.

104
00:04:01,920 --> 00:04:04,020
Words can make you sound smart,

105
00:04:04,020 --> 00:04:05,250
or they can do the opposite,

106
00:04:05,250 --> 00:04:06,930
depending on how they're deployed.

107
00:04:06,930 --> 00:04:09,360
That's why businesses hire copywriters,

108
00:04:09,360 --> 00:04:11,490
basically, salesman in print.

109
00:04:11,490 --> 00:04:14,280
Copywriters can make
insane amounts of money.

110
00:04:14,280 --> 00:04:17,550
I'm talking over $500
an hour in many cases.

111
00:04:17,550 --> 00:04:20,310
It all depends on how good
you are making connections,

112
00:04:20,310 --> 00:04:23,280
your skill with words, and
how fast you can write.

113
00:04:23,280 --> 00:04:27,210
Some charge as much as
$50,000 for just one webpage.

114
00:04:27,210 --> 00:04:29,520
You may be thinking, why so much?

115
00:04:29,520 --> 00:04:31,920
Well, it's all about value.

116
00:04:31,920 --> 00:04:34,980
If you charge $50,000 for a webpage

117
00:04:34,980 --> 00:04:37,470
and it results in a
business monthly profit

118
00:04:37,470 --> 00:04:41,160
going from 200,000 to $400,000,

119
00:04:41,160 --> 00:04:42,600
wouldn't you say it's worth it?

120
00:04:42,600 --> 00:04:46,590
It's all about leverage, making
rich clients even richer,

121
00:04:46,590 --> 00:04:48,990
then asking for your slice of the pie.

122
00:04:48,990 --> 00:04:50,820
And it's not just websites either.

123
00:04:50,820 --> 00:04:54,000
People need quality writers
for all sorts of things.

124
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,880
Everything from TikTok
scripts to threads on Twitter.

125
00:04:56,880 --> 00:05:00,030
Content is king, and the
magician behind all of this

126
00:05:00,030 --> 00:05:01,590
is often the writer.

127
00:05:01,590 --> 00:05:02,970
I know a guy named Adam.

128
00:05:02,970 --> 00:05:05,580
He started off writing blog
posts about his travels

129
00:05:05,580 --> 00:05:08,640
to earn passive income and
lived anywhere in the world.

130
00:05:08,640 --> 00:05:11,070
This later led him to
working as a copywriter

131
00:05:11,070 --> 00:05:12,510
for large influencers.

132
00:05:12,510 --> 00:05:14,880
He followed the same
strategy as Christian.

133
00:05:14,880 --> 00:05:17,670
Got one client, which
led to another and so on.

134
00:05:17,670 --> 00:05:19,650
He told me when he offers a service,

135
00:05:19,650 --> 00:05:21,570
he always tries to be exclusive

136
00:05:21,570 --> 00:05:23,910
and do it in a way that no one else could.

137
00:05:23,910 --> 00:05:26,130
There's always gonna be
someone cheaper than you,

138
00:05:26,130 --> 00:05:28,710
but not always someone more expensive.

139
00:05:28,710 --> 00:05:31,500
Find the client who can
afford to pay the premium,

140
00:05:31,500 --> 00:05:34,200
then learn to offer a world-class service.

141
00:05:34,200 --> 00:05:36,450
Job four is a SaaS software coder.

142
00:05:36,450 --> 00:05:40,110
These teens can earn between
60 and $80,000 a year.

143
00:05:40,110 --> 00:05:43,890
A guy called Sam King came on
my podcast, "Strike It Big,"

144
00:05:43,890 --> 00:05:47,400
and explained how he built a
multi-million dollar business

145
00:05:47,400 --> 00:05:49,800
without ever having a normal job.

146
00:05:49,800 --> 00:05:51,960
Instead of building a
traditional business,

147
00:05:51,960 --> 00:05:54,540
he decided to build a SaaS company.

148
00:05:54,540 --> 00:05:57,210
This stands for Software as a Service.

149
00:05:57,210 --> 00:05:59,190
Just think of how many online tools

150
00:05:59,190 --> 00:06:01,200
you use on a daily basis.

151
00:06:01,200 --> 00:06:05,520
I know I love Notion, MailChimp,
Photoshop, and many more.

152
00:06:05,520 --> 00:06:08,670
These online tools have become
such a big part of our life,

153
00:06:08,670 --> 00:06:12,090
and once the app is built,
it's almost entirely profit.

154
00:06:12,090 --> 00:06:14,490
Sam said there's so many people out there

155
00:06:14,490 --> 00:06:16,800
trying to sell the same type of product

156
00:06:16,800 --> 00:06:18,660
with such tight margin.

157
00:06:18,660 --> 00:06:21,390
It's a race to the bottom
with traditional businesses.

158
00:06:21,390 --> 00:06:23,550
People start businesses to be free

159
00:06:23,550 --> 00:06:25,440
but end up becoming slaves.

160
00:06:25,440 --> 00:06:28,590
That's why he wanted to create
a business with no inventory,

161
00:06:28,590 --> 00:06:30,690
and something that could scale infinitely.

162
00:06:30,690 --> 00:06:33,840
All he needed was a good
coder and a bit of marketing.

163
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:36,480
This is where you could
help out as a coder

164
00:06:36,480 --> 00:06:39,660
or, alternatively, come
up with the SaaS idea.

165
00:06:39,660 --> 00:06:42,360
He started by Googling and
researching the problems

166
00:06:42,360 --> 00:06:45,150
and challenges faced by
different types of businesses.

167
00:06:45,150 --> 00:06:48,540
Then had his programmer
create the perfect solution.

168
00:06:48,540 --> 00:06:51,480
He ended up building a tool
that helps people and businesses

169
00:06:51,480 --> 00:06:54,600
manage their social media
accounts, called Flick.

170
00:06:54,600 --> 00:06:57,300
So the one thing to
take from Sam's journey

171
00:06:57,300 --> 00:06:59,640
is that the most
important part of business

172
00:06:59,640 --> 00:07:02,580
is solving an issue that
affects a lot of people

173
00:07:02,580 --> 00:07:05,160
in a better way than
what's currently available.

174
00:07:05,160 --> 00:07:08,100
Job five is a content
redistribution editor.

175
00:07:08,100 --> 00:07:12,240
They can make 120 to $150,000 per year.

176
00:07:12,240 --> 00:07:15,060
Ever add some food left over
and decided just to throw it

177
00:07:15,060 --> 00:07:16,980
all in a pot and turn it into a soup?

178
00:07:16,980 --> 00:07:19,170
Well, that's what someone
I know called Josh does,

179
00:07:19,170 --> 00:07:21,000
but with video content.

180
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:23,220
The idea came to him
while he was at VidSummit.

181
00:07:23,220 --> 00:07:25,830
He was in a room with a
variety of influencers

182
00:07:25,830 --> 00:07:28,800
when suddenly a light
bulb went off in his head.

183
00:07:28,800 --> 00:07:30,750
He didn't have to create his own content.

184
00:07:30,750 --> 00:07:33,300
He just took existing
videos and remixed them

185
00:07:33,300 --> 00:07:36,300
for YouTubers that wanted
to post short-form content.

186
00:07:36,300 --> 00:07:38,940
He took podcasts and YouTube videos

187
00:07:38,940 --> 00:07:41,280
and made them TikTok
and Instagram friendly,

188
00:07:41,280 --> 00:07:44,760
giving his clients the ability
to reach much wider audiences

189
00:07:44,760 --> 00:07:48,150
without actually producing
any new content themselves.

190
00:07:48,150 --> 00:07:50,160
It's called content redistribution.

191
00:07:50,160 --> 00:07:52,890
It's like recycling,
but in the digital age.

192
00:07:52,890 --> 00:07:54,630
It doesn't take too much time,

193
00:07:54,630 --> 00:07:56,760
but large creators don't want the hassle

194
00:07:56,760 --> 00:07:58,560
of editing everything themselves.

195
00:07:58,560 --> 00:08:00,780
Josh later went on to hire team members

196
00:08:00,780 --> 00:08:04,200
so that he could serve more
clients and increase his income.

197
00:08:04,200 --> 00:08:06,240
Job six is a website developer.

198
00:08:06,240 --> 00:08:08,670
Teens doing this can earn
an average annual salary

199
00:08:08,670 --> 00:08:12,750
of around 80 to $150,000 per year.

200
00:08:12,750 --> 00:08:15,360
For many businesses, their
website is their front door,

201
00:08:15,360 --> 00:08:17,760
so they wanna make it
as stylish as possible.

202
00:08:17,760 --> 00:08:20,460
I've got a friend named
Chris who lives out in Italy.

203
00:08:20,460 --> 00:08:24,150
He decided he wanted to niche
down into the e-learning space

204
00:08:24,150 --> 00:08:26,460
and focus on building marketing funnels.

205
00:08:26,460 --> 00:08:29,340
A good website developer knows
that if you keep your clients

206
00:08:29,340 --> 00:08:32,280
on a monthly retainer, you
can earn passive income

207
00:08:32,280 --> 00:08:34,800
just by doing small tweaks here and there.

208
00:08:34,800 --> 00:08:36,630
Chris told me that the best way forward

209
00:08:36,630 --> 00:08:38,700
is to start a subscription business

210
00:08:38,700 --> 00:08:40,147
with reoccurring revenue.

211
00:08:40,147 --> 00:08:41,640
"Think Netflix," he said.

212
00:08:41,640 --> 00:08:44,610
The best job is one that
requires very little maintenance.

213
00:08:44,610 --> 00:08:47,010
You just keep clients
on a retainer of voila.

214
00:08:47,010 --> 00:08:48,630
He now has enough passive income

215
00:08:48,630 --> 00:08:50,910
to live almost anywhere in the world.

216
00:08:50,910 --> 00:08:53,370
He often travels to cheap
countries like Thailand

217
00:08:53,370 --> 00:08:55,890
where he can live on
less than $1,000 a month.

218
00:08:55,890 --> 00:08:58,650
He doesn't focus on earning
as much money as possible.

219
00:08:58,650 --> 00:09:00,510
He said that's just a trap.

220
00:09:00,510 --> 00:09:03,120
The point of making money
is to buy yourself freedom.

221
00:09:03,120 --> 00:09:05,400
Job seven is a Twitter manager.

222
00:09:05,400 --> 00:09:09,600
Teens can earn around 60 to
$80,000 per year doing this job.

223
00:09:09,600 --> 00:09:12,570
Twitter seems to be the
hottest social media nowadays,

224
00:09:12,570 --> 00:09:15,240
especially since the
whole Elon Musk takeover.

225
00:09:15,240 --> 00:09:17,520
I know a college dropout called Sean

226
00:09:17,520 --> 00:09:20,760
who wasted a lot of his
time trolling on Twitter

227
00:09:20,760 --> 00:09:22,147
until he asked himself,

228
00:09:22,147 --> 00:09:25,110
"What if I could actually
make a job out of this?"

229
00:09:25,110 --> 00:09:27,960
So he decided to become a Twitter expert.

230
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:30,150
He took a lot of time to study the content

231
00:09:30,150 --> 00:09:32,227
put out by some of the best creators.

232
00:09:32,227 --> 00:09:34,200
"Don't just look at the
reason stuff though,"

233
00:09:34,200 --> 00:09:35,033
he told me.

234
00:09:35,033 --> 00:09:37,770
"Look at the post that
really made them blow up.

235
00:09:37,770 --> 00:09:40,530
Then study it. That's
what you want to go for."

236
00:09:40,530 --> 00:09:43,260
He said two of the best ways
to blow up nowadays on Twitter

237
00:09:43,260 --> 00:09:45,270
is to create threads and host spaces.

238
00:09:45,270 --> 00:09:47,340
You need to be able to
capture people's attention

239
00:09:47,340 --> 00:09:49,920
with as few words as
possible and hook them in,

240
00:09:49,920 --> 00:09:51,840
and that takes a lot of practice.

241
00:09:51,840 --> 00:09:54,420
But this is a very
valuable skill to learn.

242
00:09:54,420 --> 00:09:57,330
Just like the others, he said
he takes multiple clients

243
00:09:57,330 --> 00:09:59,850
on at the same time and, much like Chris,

244
00:09:59,850 --> 00:10:01,200
keeps them on a retainer.

245
00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:04,590
Job 7.5 is an executive assistant.

246
00:10:04,590 --> 00:10:06,360
It's a bonus because it can become

247
00:10:06,360 --> 00:10:08,040
more than just an online job.

248
00:10:08,040 --> 00:10:12,330
These teams can make 90
to $110,000 per year.

249
00:10:12,330 --> 00:10:14,850
You'll be doing everything
from scheduling appointments

250
00:10:14,850 --> 00:10:17,070
to making small decisions everyday.

